x4freetext: Sample irradiated using TR 19/9
negative ion variable energy  cyclotron (Advanced
Cyclotron Systems Inc., Richmond, BC) at the Edmonton
PET Centre.
High purity natural Ti foils. 17 high purity samples
with  thickness of 11.8 mu-m were used.
HPGe detector (Ortec model GEM35P4-S) placed
in a near 4Pi (except  the detector entry) low
background shield. Measurements were performed at a
25 cm source-detector distance (SDD) with dead-times
less than  5%.
The TR 19/9 cyclotron allows for extraction of
deuterons from a  nominal 6.8-9.7 MeV. Lower energies
were achieved by using  either a 25 mu-m or 125 mu-m
aluminum foil degrader. In addition, a 25 mu-m
aluminum foil vacuum window was in  place for all
irradiations
Statistical uncertainty
Systematic uncertainty in Ti foil thickness
Syst. uncertainty in efficiency calibration
Systematic uncertainty in beam current
Systematic uncertainty in decay data
Systematic uncertainty in peak fitting
Total uncertainty calculated as a quadratic
sum of all uncertainties
